article.description:
Maureece Rice scored 14 points and Mike Hall had 12 points and 11 rebounds, leading No. 19 George Washington to
a 72-60 victory over Temple on Wednesday night in the Atlantic 10
Conference opener for both teams.
article.headline: Hall, Rice lead No. 19 Colonials past Temple
article.linkText: Hall, Rice lead No. 19 Colonials past Temple
article.story: PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- George Washington's patience and poise against Temple's famed matchup zone paid off. Maureece Rice scored 14 points and Mike Hall had 12 points and 11 rebounds, leading the Colonials (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today; No. 20 AP) to a 72-60 victory Wednesday night in the Atlantic 10 Conference opener for both teams. Pops Mensah-Bonsu and Danilo Pinnock each added 12 points for George Washington (9-1). "The key was to control the tempo and that's difficult against their matchup zone," Colonials coach Karl Hobbs said. Mardy Collins had 19 points and Antywane Robinson added 13 for Temple (6-5). "We shot the ball real bad. The defense was all right," Temple coach John Chaney said. George Washington climbed to No. 12 in the AP poll by winning its first eight games, but fell eight spots after a 21-point loss to then-No. 19 North Carolina State last Friday. The Colonials started slowly against Temple, but began to pull away in the second half. Rice, a Philadelphia native, hit a 3-pointer 5 minutes in to give George Washington its first double-digit lead, 44-32. A 3-pointer by Carl Elliott made it 49-34. But Temple answered with a 10-0 run as Robinson hit two 3-pointers and a jumper. Pinnock's three-point play put George Washington ahead 53-44. Hall then made a no-look pass to Mensah-Bonsu for a layup and hit a 3-pointer to extend the Colonials' lead to 60-46 with 4:26 left. Temple couldn't make another run. The Owls missed 13 of their first 14 shots from beyond the arc, before Robinson hit two 3s. They finished 5-of-19 from 3-point range. Temple leads the all-time series 45-15 against George Washington, but has lost the last four meetings. "The trend is we don't have a good team," Chaney said. "They're a ranked team. They're supposed to beat us." Rice was a three-time state scoring champion at Strawberry Mansion High School and scored 2,681 career points, breaking Wilt Chamberlain's Philadelphia career scoring record. "Since I've been at George Washington the last five years, he's made the biggest progress in terms of maturity and development," Hobbs said of Rice, a sophomore guard. "He's a special guy. He came up big." George Washington outscored Temple 14-7 over the final 6 minutes of the first half to take a 34-30 lead. A layup by Pinnock off an alley-oop pass from Rice gave the Colonials their first lead, 24-23. There was plenty of bad shooting and sloppy turnovers early for both sides. Temple's sticky defense gave George Washington trouble at the start as the Colonials had just two baskets in the opening 5 minutes. But George Washington came in ready to play after the disappointing loss at N.C. State. Hobbs held a couple of long practices to make sure the team wouldn't let down against Temple. "We knew we had to pick up our intensity as far as practice was concerned," Mensah-Bonsu said. "We didn't do what we had to do to be physically and mentally prepared against N.C. State. We had to practice good habits." Temple was coming off a 22-point loss to No. 3 Villanova last Saturday, a game the Owls were in until the Wildcats took control at the end. Temple was seeking its second win against a Top 25 opponent this season, having beaten then-No. 22 Alabama 68-58 on Dec. 10. Inconsistency has been a problem for Temple, which has made five NCAA regional finals under Chaney, but hasn't been to the NCAA tournament since 2001.
